# Docs sync rules (docs-as-code)

When you change code, **update docs as part of the same change set** when the change affects how someone uses, runs, or integrates with the system.

## When docs MUST be updated

- **API changes**: new/removed endpoints, request/response shape changes, auth/headers, error codes.
- **Behavior changes**: defaults, ordering, side effects, data deletion semantics, polling/streaming behavior.
- **Setup/runtime changes**: env vars, ports, local dev steps, required services, build/run commands.
- **UI/UX changes**: new pages/flows, renamed navigation items, new constraints/limits that users will notice.

## What to update (minimum)

- **README / docs**: update the affected section(s) (install/run, usage, troubleshooting).
- **Examples**: keep example requests/bodies in sync with actual handlers.
- **Schema/SQL**: if DB schema or RLS invariants changed, update the relevant `.sql` / rules doc.

## How to write the doc update

- Be **specific and copy/paste-able**: include exact paths, commands, routes, and JSON bodies.
- Prefer **small, local edits** near the relevant section over creating new docs.
- If there is **no doc impact**, state that explicitly (e.g. “No user-facing/API changes”).

